<div class="container">
    <h1>Objects in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>An <strong>object</strong> is an instance of a class. Objects contain data in the form of <strong>properties</strong> and can perform actions through <strong>methods</strong>.</p>

    <h2>Example: Creating and Using Objects</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Creating Objects from a Class</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying.");
    }
}

// Creating objects
Student student1 = new Student();
student1.Name = "Alice";
student1.Age = 20;
student1.Study();

Student student2 = new Student();
student2.Name = "Bob";
student2.Age = 22;
student2.Study();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Points About Objects</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Objects are instances of a class with their own data.</li>
        <li>Each object can call methods and access properties defined in the class.</li>
        <li>Objects allow you to model real-world entities in your programs.</li>
        <li>Constructors can be used to initialize objects with specific values.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
